{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox person | image = | caption = | birth_name = Jillian Leigh Bell | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1984|4|25}} | birth_place = [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], U.S. | occupation = {{hlist|Actress|screenwriter|comedian}} | yearsactive = 2006–present }} '''Jillian Leigh Bell'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jilliandeltoro/status/475837305677045761|title=Jillian Bell on Twitter|work=Twitter|accessdate=December 22, 2015}}</ref> (born April 25, 1984)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thespazmatics.com/jillian-bells-30th/|title=Jillian Bell’s 30th|publisher=|accessdate=December 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/lennyjacobson/status/592034394707271680|title=Lenny Jacobson on Twitter|work=Twitter|accessdate=December 22, 2015}}</ref> is an American comedian, actress, and screenwriter. She is best known for her recurring roles as Jillian Belk on ''[[Workaholics]]'' and Dixie on the final season of ''[[Eastbound & Down]]'', as well as appearing in ''[[22 Jump Street]]'' and ''[[Fist Fight]]''.
==Early life== Bell was born and raised in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], the daughter of Tanzy and Ron Bell.<ref name=variety>{{cite web|author=Justin Shady |url=https://variety.com/2012/scene/people-news/bell-workaholic-aces-master-class-1118056715/ |title=Bell: Workaholic aces ‘Master’ class |publisher=Variety |date=July 24, 2012 |accessdate=October 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lvol.com/gossip/2012/lvgossip305.html |title=Claire Voyant - Past Column from July 06, 2012 |publisher=Lvol.com |date= |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Her grandmother was [[Romanians|Romanian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jimmy-mcnamara/from-curb-to-partners-jil_b_1859850.html|title=From ''Curb'' to ''Partners'': Jillian Bell - Jimmy McNamara|date=September 6, 2012|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=December 22, 2015}}</ref> Bell began studying [[Improvisational theatre|improv]] at the age of eight.<ref name=huffpo>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jimmy-mcnamara/from-curb-to-partners-jil_b_1859850.html |title=Jimmy McNamara: From Curb to Partners: Jillian Bell |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=September 6, 2012 |accessdate=October 21, 2013}}</ref> She graduated from [[Bishop Gorman High School]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://issuu.com/bishopgorman/docs/gazette_summer_2012|title=Seven Questions With Jillian Bell '02|work=Bishop Gorman High School Alumni Newsletter|date=Summer 2012|page=12|accessdate=February 10, 2014}}</ref> After high school, she moved to [[Los Angeles, California]] and became a member of the [[Groundlings]].<ref name=variety/>
==Career== An alum of The Straitjacket Society in Los Angeles, CA, Jillian auditioned for ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', and though she did not join the cast, she became a writer for the show in 2009 for the [[Saturday Night Live (season 35)|thirty-fifth season]].<ref name=variety/> The same year Bell appeared in an episode of ''[[Curb Your Enthusiasm]]'' as an assistant who wears revealing clothing at work.<ref name=huffpo/>
In 2011, she began to play "Jillian Belk" on the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[Workaholics]]''. Film director [[Paul Thomas Anderson]] noticed her in ''Workaholics'' and cast her in a small role in his 2012 film, ''[[The Master (2012 film)|The Master]]'' and yet again in another small role in his 2014 film, ''[[Inherent Vice (film)|Inherent Vice]]''.<ref name=variety/> She had a recurring role as Dixie in the fourth and final season of ''[[Eastbound and Down]]''. In 2014, she appeared in ''[[22 Jump Street]]'' alongside [[Jonah Hill]] and [[Channing Tatum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/workaholics-star-jillian-bell-joins-jonah-hill-channing-tatum-in-22-jump-street-exclusive/ |title='Workaholics' Star Jillian Bell Joins Jonah Hill, Channing Tatum in '22 Jump Street' (Exclusive) |publisher=TheWrap |date=September 12, 2013 |accessdate=February 10, 2014}}</ref> In 2015, she co-starred in ''[[Goosebumps (film)|Goosebumps]]'' and ''[[The Night Before (2015 film)|The Night Before]]''.
In January 2016, [[Comedy Central]] debuted a new series, ''[[Idiotsitter]]'', in which Bell portrays the constantly misbehaving daughter of wealthy parents; her character, Gene Russell, is serving time under [[house arrest]], and is being mentored by Billie Brown ([[Charlotte Newhouse]]), who is hired by Gene's parents. ''Idiotsitter'' was launched as a web series in early 2014, before being picked up in June 2014 by Comedy Central for network airing.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Liz Shannon|title=If Comedy Central's 'Idiotsitter' is Half as Funny As Talking to Its Creators, It Could Be the Funniest Show on TV|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/comedy-central-idiotsitter-creators-jillian-bell-charlotte-newhouse-interview-it-could-be-the-funniest-show-on-tv-20160114|website=Indiewire|accessdate=March 7, 2016|date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>
