{{Infobox person | name = Philippa Boyens | image = Philippa Boyens.jpg | caption =Boyens in 2012 | occupation = Screenwriter, film producer | birth_date = | birth_place = | years_active = 2001–present}}
'''Philippa Boyens''', [[New Zealand Order of Merit|MNZM]], is a<!--awards and nominations don't belong here--> [[New Zealand]] [[screenwriter]] and [[Film producer|producer]] who co-wrote the [[screenplay]] for [[Peter Jackson]]'s films [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|''The Lord of the Rings'' series]], ''[[King Kong (2005 film)|King Kong]]'', ''[[The Lovely Bones (film)|The Lovely Bones]]'', and the three-part film ''[[The Hobbit (film series)|The Hobbit]]'',<ref name=Moviefone>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Drew|title=Peter Jackson and Philippa Boyens on 'The Hobbit,' a Missing Elf, and What's Next (EXCLUSIVE)|url=http://news.moviefone.com/2014/12/19/peter-jackson-philippa-boyens-the-hobbit-interview|accessdate=25 December 2014|work=Moviefone|agency=AOL Inc.|issue=19 December 2014|publisher=Moviefone|date=19 December 2014|ref=http://news.moviefone.com/bloggers/drew-taylor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224182608/http://news.moviefone.com/2014/12/19/peter-jackson-philippa-boyens-the-hobbit-interview|archive-date=2014-12-24|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> all with Jackson and [[Fran Walsh]].<ref name="The Huffington Post">{{cite news|last1=Sobczak|first1=Marcin J.|title=The Producer's Work: An Interview With Philippa Boyens|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/marcin-j-sobczak/the-producers-work-an-int_1_b_6268066.html?ir=India|accessdate=25 December 2014|work=The Huffington Post|issue=5 December 2014|publisher=huffingtonpost.com|date=5 December 2014|ref=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/marcin-j-sobczak/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225074100/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/marcin-j-sobczak/the-producers-work-an-int_1_b_6268066.html?ir=India|archive-date=2014-12-25|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref><ref name="3 News">{{cite news|last1=Rodger|first1=Kate|title=Full interview: Peter Jackson, Philippa Boyens on finishing the Hobbit movies|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/entertainment/full-interview-peter-jackson-philippa-boyens-on-finishing-the-hobbit-movies-2014120215|accessdate=25 December 2014|work=3news.co.nz|agency=3 News Newzealand|issue=2 December 2014|publisher=3 News Newzealand|date=2 December 2014|ref=http://www.3news.co.nz/author/kate-rodger|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225074059/http://www.3news.co.nz/entertainment/full-interview-peter-jackson-philippa-boyens-on-finishing-the-hobbit-movies-2014120215|archive-date=2014-12-25|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref><ref name="Now Magazine Toronto">{{cite web|last1=Wilner|first1=Norman|title=Q&A: Peter Jackson, Philippa Boyens & Lee Pace|url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/features/peter-jackson-philippa-boyens-lee-pace|website=https://nowtoronto.com|publisher=Now Magazine|accessdate=25 December 2014|ref=https://nowtoronto.com/topics/norman-wilner}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name="Los Angeles Times">{{cite news|last1=Clark|first1=Noelene|title=‘The Hobbit': Peter Jackson, Philippa Boyens on ‘Five Armies’ ending|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/movies/the-hobbit-peter-jackson-philippa-boyens-on-five-armies-ending/#/0|accessdate=25 December 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=Los Angeles Times|issue=18 December 2014|publisher=Herocomplex.latimes.com|date=18 December 2014|ref=https://twitter.com/noeleneclark|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227072421/http://herocomplex.latimes.com/movies/the-hobbit-peter-jackson-philippa-boyens-on-five-armies-ending/#/0|archive-date=2014-12-27|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>
She, Jackson, and Walsh won the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]] for ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]'' at the [[76th Academy Awards]] in 2004. She was also co-producer in every one of Jackson's films since ''King Kong'', and in ''[[District 9]]''. Prior to screenwriting, Boyens worked in theater as a playwright, teacher, producer and editor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/geekdad/2012/12/philippa-boyens |title=Hobbit Week: A Conversation with Hobbit Screenwriter Philippa Boyens |publisher=Wired.com |author=[[Ethan Gilsdorf]] |accessdate=28 April 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130114030036/http://www.wired.com/geekdad/2012/12/philippa-boyens |archivedate=January 14, 2013 }}</ref> She also spent time as director of the [[New Zealand Writers Guild]].<ref name="PBio">{{cite web|url=http://www.in.com/philippa-boyens/biography-222901.html|title=Phillipa Boyens biodata|publisher=In.com|accessdate=28 April 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113100613/http://www.in.com/philippa-boyens/biography-222901.html|archivedate=13 November 2013|df=}}</ref>
Boyens attended [[Massey High School]] and was latter a part-time student at the [[University of Auckland]], graduating with a BA in English and History in 1994. She received a Distinguished Alumni Award from the university in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alumni.auckland.ac.nz/uoa/af-phillippa-boyens|title=Distinguished Alumni Profiles - Philippa Boyens|publisher=[[University of Auckland]]|accessdate=2 January 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220002827/http://www.alumni.auckland.ac.nz/uoa/af-phillippa-boyens|archivedate=20 February 2012|df=}}</ref>
She has three children, daughter Phoebe Gittins and son Calum Gittins (both with actor [[Paul Gittins]]), and a second son, Isaac Miller. Phoebe appeared as a Hobbit in ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring]]'', one of George Harvey's victims in ''[[The Lovely Bones (film)|The Lovely Bones]]'', and a wench in the [[Prancing Pony]] in ''[[The Hobbit: The Desolation of Smaug]]''; Calum appeared as [[List of original characters in The Lord of the Rings film series#Haleth|Haleth]] in ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers]]'';<ref>{{IMDb name|id=0101991|name=Philippa Boyens}}</ref> and Isaac appeared as a young Hobbit in a flashback of the Old Took's party in the extended edition of ''[[The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey]]''.
==Work on ''Lord of the Rings''== Boyens first became a Tolkien fan as a child. When she came on board to help the writing team on ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'', she had already read the book seven times.<ref name="PBio"/>
