'''''Vorhor, the Green Wave''''' is one of the most famous paintings by [[France|French]] artist [[Georges Lacombe (painter)|Georges Lacombe]]. It is currently located in the [[Indianapolis Museum of Art]], which is in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Georges Lacombe|url=http://www.artlikbez.com/Artist/Georges-Lacombe/d3412a903cbffef0632ed6de73135e9a/georges-lacombe.html?lang=en|publisher=Artlikbez|accessdate=30 December 2012}}</ref> Painted 1896-97, Lacombe used egg tempera and the inspiration of [[Ukiyo-e|Japanese prints]] to depict the cliffs of Vorhor in [[Brittany]].<ref name=ima/>
==Description== North of [[Pont-Aven]], Lacombe found this dramatic crag overlooking the sea and rendered it even more spectacular with vivid hues of turquoise, mauve, and gold. He also anthropomorphized the rocks, finding human shapes in them, and transformed the waves into decorative patterns similar to Japanese prints.<ref name=lee>{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Ellen Wardwell|last2=Robinson|first2=Anne|title=Indianapolis Museum of Art: Highlights of the Collection|publisher=Indianapolis Museum of Art|location=Indianapolis|year=2005|isbn=0936260777}}</ref> The back of the canvas bears an atelier monogram.<ref name=ima/>
==Historical information== In 1892, Lacombe first encountered [[Post-Impressionism]], and was immediately smitten. He fully embraced [[Paul Gauguin|Gauguin's]] insistence that artists be allowed to reinterpret nature when creating a series of coastal paintings between 1893 and 1897. The influence of [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]] on Lacombe can be seen in the foreboding with which he imbued the narrow gap and pounding waves.<ref name=day>{{cite book|last=Day|first=Holliday T.|title=Indianapolis Museum of Art Collections Handbook|year=1988|publisher=[[Indianapolis Museum of Art]]|location=[[Indianapolis]]|isbn=0936260203}}</ref>
===Acquisition=== Sylvie Mora-Lacombe inherited the painting upon her father's death. It was purchased by the IMA in 1984 with the assistance of the Alliance of the Indianapolis Museum of Art, where it was given the acquisition number 1984.202.<ref name=ima>{{cite web|title=Vorhor, the Green Wave|url=http://www.imamuseum.org/art/collections/artwork/vorhor-green-wave-lacombe-georges|publisher=[[Indianapolis Museum of Art]]|accessdate=30 December 2012}}</ref>
